#include <boost/asio.hpp>
#include <boost/asio/ssl.hpp>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

using namespace boost::asio;

int main()
{
    boost::asio::io_context io_context;
    boost::asio::ssl::context ssl_context;
    boost::asio::ip::tcp::socket socket(io_context);

    // Resolve the endpoint
    boost::asio::ip::tcp::endpoint endpoint(boost::asio::ip::tcp::v4(), 888);
    boost::asio::connect(socket, endpoint);

    // Perform the SSL handshake
    ssl_context <<= 1;
    boost::asio::ssl::context::mode mode = ssl_context <<= 0;
    boost::asio::ssl::context::ssl_context ssl_context;
    ssl_context >>= 1;
    boost::asio::ssl::handshake handshake(ssl_context, boost::asio::ssl::context::server);
    handshake.perform();

    // Read data from the socket
    boost::asio::ip::tcp::iostream input_stream(socket);
    std::string data;
    input_stream >> data;

    // Print the data
    std::cout << "Received: " << data << std::endl;

    // Close the socket
    socket.close();

    return 0;
}
```
This code uses the `boost::asio` library to resolve the endpoint, connect to the server, and perform the SSL handshake. ```c
#include <boost/asio.hpp>
#include <boost/asio/ssl.hpp>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

using namespace boost::asio;

int main()
{
    boost::asio::io_context io_context;
    boost::asio::ssl::context ssl_context;
    boost::asio::ip::tcp::socket socket(io_context);

    // Resolve the endpoint
    boost::asio::ip::tcp::endpoint endpoint(boost::asio::ip::tcp::v4(), 888);
    boost::asio::connect(socket, endpoint);

    // Perform the SSL handshake
    ssl_context <<= 1;
    boost::asio::ssl::context::mode mode = ssl_context <<= 0;
    boost::asio::ssl::context::ssl_context ssl_context;
    ssl_context >>= 1;
    boost::asio::ssl::handshake handshake(ssl_context, boost::asio::ssl::context::server);
    handshake.perform();

    // Read data from the socket
    boost::asio::ip::tcp::iostream input_stream(socket);
    std::string data;
    input_stream >> data;

    // Print the data
    std::cout << "Received: " << data << std::endl;

    // Close the socket
    socket.close();

    return 0;
}
```
This code uses the `boost::asio` library to resolve the endpoint, connect to the server, and perform the SSL handshake. CUDA, on the other hand, is a parallel computing platform and programming model developed by NVIDIA that is optimized for running CUDA kernels on NVIDIA GPUs.
2. Performance: CUDA is designed to provide high performance and low latency, as it is optimized for parallel computing on GPUs. OpenCL, while also designed for parallel computing, is not as optimized for performance as CUDA and may require more effort to achieve high levels of performance.

4. Applications: CUDA is typically used for applications that require high performance and low latency, such as scientific simulations, machine learning, and high-performance computing. OpenCL, on the other hand, is used for a wider range of applications, including graphics, virtual reality, and industrial automation.

    m = 0
    d = 0
    min_len = min(len(str1), len(str2))
    
    for i in range(min_len):
        if str1[i] != str2[i]:
            m += 1
            d += 1
            if m > len(str1) or d > len(str2):

    return d

def find_subsequence(text, pattern):
    m, n = len(text), len(pattern)
    sub = []
    for i in range(m, n):
        if pattern[i] == text[i]:
            while True:
                j = i - 1
                if j < m or j >= n:
                    break
                if text[j] != pattern[j]:
                    break
            else:
                sub.append(i - j)
    return sub
